issue.title: Hash table variants and optimizations

labels.name: CLA Signed
labels.description: This label is managed by the Facebook bot. Authors need to sign the CLA before a PR can be reviewed.

issue.body:
Introduces an alternative F14 style interleave layour for HashTable. This layout alternates tags and pointers to payload. Each group takes two cache lines: 16 bytes of tags, 8 * 48 bytes of pointers in the first cache line and 8*48 bits of pointers in the second cache line. A hash table that is expected to hit frequently, i.e. a group by table, will benefit from this layout since the tags and pointers most often share one cache miss and always share the TLB lookup.

Adds optional counters for hash lookups and collisions.

simplifies the hashProbe concept by passing the table as an argument as opposed to different fields of the table.

Uses SIMD for an array hash table probe. Previously this was limited to group by tables.

Remove dependency on own argument/attribute for callee and instantiation hints

Summary:
Currently instantiations and callee hints depend on their attributes/argument, and if a property or argument depends on this hint, this can cause self-cycles to occur: for example, `g(function f() { return 1 })` induces a cycle between `f` and itself, because `f` depends on `g(function f() { ... })`. This diff makes it so that even synthesizable arguments or attributes aren't depended on if they themselves are what is being hinted.

commits.message:
Add support for LiveData observability

Summary:
# Context

In this diff we are adding the initial support for live data observability.

## API

At this moment we have two API proposals:

```
fun <T> ComponentScope.useLiveData(liveData: LiveData<T>): T?

fun <T> ComponentScope.useLiveData(
    liveData: LiveData<T>,
    vararg keys: Any?,
    initialValue: () -> T?
): T?
```

Some examples of how it could look like to be used:

```
val viewState = useLiveData(viewStateLiveData) ?: error("should not be null")

val viewState = useLiveData(viewStateLiveData) { ViewState("hello", ..) } ?: error("should not be null")
```

## Behavior

- The `LiveData` is only be observed when the `Lifecycle` is in an `Active` state `(>= STARTED)`.
- The `LiveData` stops propagating updates when the `Lifecycle` is in an inactive state (`PAUSED/STOPPED`).
- The `LiveData` can resume updates observation when navigating between `PAUSED/STOPPED` to `STARTED/RESUMED` states.
- The `LiveData` stops being observed (and removes the observer) when the `Lifecycle` moves to `Destroyed`
- The `LiveData` stops being observed (and removed the observer) if the `ComponentTree/LithoView` is released (since the `useEffect` is cleaned up).

## Hooking the `LifecycleOwner`.

When observing a `LiveData` we need a reference to the appropriate `LifecycleOwner` (which is usually an `Activity` or `Fragment`).  The way I'm proposing to plug this is that we would store the `LifecycleOwner` as a `TreeProp` when create the `LithoView` with the `AOSPLithoLifecycleProvider`. This would allow the clients to specifiy for their case which is the most appropriate `LifecycleOwner`.

This goes along also with the side initiative we have to make people use more the `AOSPLithoLifecycleProvider` so that they have more reliable visibility callbacks.

**Things to note/Open Questions**
- **Usage of `keys`**:  At this moment I don't see the point of `keys`; in theory it would be a way to invalidate the observation, but it would simply trigger a new observation afterwards. I just added it here because the `useFlow` also has it, but Im failing to see a good use case for it. If we don't see any advantage for now, I would propose to remove it.

- **Null returns**: The `LiveData` API always return nullable types. For that reason our API is forced to also return nulls. I don't think we can do much here, but let me know otherwise. This will though force clients to handle with nullability explicitly. For example:

```
val viewState = useLiveData(liveData) ?: error("should not be null")
```
- **useFlow not using tree props**: astreet I did not find any usage of `TreeProps` in the `useFlow` - but maybe I'm looking to the wrong places. So at this moment, there is no unified solution (and I'm not even sure we need one).

- **Custom lifecycle owner**: astreet nicholeic I believe this might have a use case, but I wanted to explore later on. One possible way out, would be to give the ability to pass a specific `LifecycleOwner` and if so, it would override the default one.

labels.name: CLA Signed

issue.body:
Put together a skeleton of Aggregation Fuzzer. Similar to Expression Fuzzer, but
intended to test aggregate functions and aggregation operator itself.

This initial version generates single global aggregation using one aggregate
function and runs it on a single randomly generated vector. It already found 2
crashes in approx_percentile and approx_most_frequent: #3099 and #3101.

Follow-up PRs will extend the Aggregation Fuzzer to
- generate many equivalent plans and verify they return same results (this logic
  would be similar to AggregationTestBase::testAggregations);
- run aggregations on multiple batches of data;
- run both global and partial aggregations using multiple grouping keys;
- run aggregations using multiple aggregate functions;
- support aggregate functions with generic signatures.

The structure of the Aggregation Fuzzer is similar to Expression Fuzzer.

- AggregationFuzzerTest is the entry point with the main() method.
- AggregationFuzzerTest hard-codes the skip-list and calls
  AggregationFuzzerRunner::run().
- AggregationFuzzerRunner builds a list of signatures taking care to
  process --only list and skip-list and calls aggregationFuzzer() from
  AggregationFuzzer.h
- AggregationFuzzer(signatures, seed)::go runs the main loop. Each iteration
  picks random signature, creates a query plan and executes it.

  1: map<i32, set<string>> (cpp.type = "std::unordered_map<int32_t, std::unordered_set<std::string>>") field

This generates the following type tag

```

When we loop over the `Foo::field`, value type `std::unordered_set<std::string>` won't match type tag `type::set<type::string>>`, which confused op library.

  1: map<i32, UnorderedSetString> (cpp.template = "std::unordered_map") field
}
```

So that it generates the correct type tag

```
type::cpp_type<

  type::map<type::i32_t, type::cpp_type<std::unordered_set<std::string>,

Boradcom have two bcm config settings for SAI_PORT_ATTR_HW_LANE_LIST (aka HwLaneList attribute in FBOSS PortApi):
sai_port_pmap_phy_lanes: 1 ==> SAI_PORT_ATTR_HW_LANE_LIST means physical port list
sai_port_pmap_phy_lanes: 0 ==> SAI_PORT_ATTR_HW_LANE_LIST means serdes/pmd lane list

In FBOSS SAI, we need "sai_port_pmap_phy_lanes: 0". However, it does not work well with flexport feature to add/remove 400G port. Although the long term fix is to support flexport with "sai_port_pmap_phy_lanes: 0" (tracked by CS00012268803), we need to live with "sai_port_pmap_phy_lanes: 1" in the short term. Since we still need the port pmd lane info in our fboss port programming logics, Broadcom introduces this extension attribute SAI_PORT_ATTR_SERDES_LANE_LIST to always return the pmd lane info for a port.

commits.message:
Add thread memory tracker util class to compute object size

Summary:
Add a util class `ThreadMemoryTracker` to help compute object size when enabling size-awareness.
The basic idea is
- Use Jemalloc util function(`thread.allocatedp` and `thread.deallocatedp`) to calculate allocated memory and deallocated memory in the current thread:
```
  memory usage = allocate memory - deallocated memory
```
- Get the currently used memory before and after the object construction, the difference is the object memory:
```
   get before memory usage
   ...construct object
   get after memory usage
   object size = after memory usage - before memory usage

```

Example:
```
// initialize memory tracker only at the beginning
ThreadMemoryTracke tMemTracker;
...

auto beforeMemUsage = tMemTracker.getMemUsageBytes();
...construct the object
auto afterMemUsage = tMemTracker.getMemUsageBytes();
auto objectSize = LIKELY(afterMemUsage > beforeMemUsage)
                        ? (afterMemUsage - beforeMemUsage)
                        : 0;
```

issue.body:
Introduces an alternative F14 style interleave layour for HashTable. This layout alternates tags and pointers to payload. Each group takes two cache lines: 16 bytes of tags, 8 * 48 bytes of pointers in the first cache line and 8*48 bits of pointers in the second cache line. A hash table that is expected to hit frequently, i.e. a group by table, will benefit from this layout since the tags and pointers most often share one cache miss and always share the TLB lookup.

Adds optional counters for hash lookups and collisions.

simplifies the hashProbe concept by passing the table as an argument as opposed to different fields of the table.

Uses SIMD for an array hash table probe. Previously this was limited to group by tables.

commits.message:
Add support for LiveData observability

Summary:
# Context

In this diff we are adding the initial support for live data observability.

## API

At this moment we have two API proposals:

```
fun <T> ComponentScope.useLiveData(liveData: LiveData<T>): T?

fun <T> ComponentScope.useLiveData(
    liveData: LiveData<T>,
    vararg keys: Any?,
    initialValue: () -> T?
): T?
```

Some examples of how it could look like to be used:

```
val viewState = useLiveData(viewStateLiveData) ?: error("should not be null")

val viewState = useLiveData(viewStateLiveData) { ViewState("hello", ..) } ?: error("should not be null")
```

## Behavior

- The `LiveData` is only be observed when the `Lifecycle` is in an `Active` state `(>= STARTED)`.
- The `LiveData` stops propagating updates when the `Lifecycle` is in an inactive state (`PAUSED/STOPPED`).
- The `LiveData` can resume updates observation when navigating between `PAUSED/STOPPED` to `STARTED/RESUMED` states.
- The `LiveData` stops being observed (and removes the observer) when the `Lifecycle` moves to `Destroyed`
- The `LiveData` stops being observed (and removed the observer) if the `ComponentTree/LithoView` is released (since the `useEffect` is cleaned up).

## Hooking the `LifecycleOwner`.

When observing a `LiveData` we need a reference to the appropriate `LifecycleOwner` (which is usually an `Activity` or `Fragment`).  The way I'm proposing to plug this is that we would store the `LifecycleOwner` as a `TreeProp` when create the `LithoView` with the `AOSPLithoLifecycleProvider`. This would allow the clients to specifiy for their case which is the most appropriate `LifecycleOwner`.

This goes along also with the side initiative we have to make people use more the `AOSPLithoLifecycleProvider` so that they have more reliable visibility callbacks.

**Things to note/Open Questions**
- **Usage of `keys`**:  At this moment I don't see the point of `keys`; in theory it would be a way to invalidate the observation, but it would simply trigger a new observation afterwards. I just added it here because the `useFlow` also has it, but Im failing to see a good use case for it. If we don't see any advantage for now, I would propose to remove it.

- **Null returns**: The `LiveData` API always return nullable types. For that reason our API is forced to also return nulls. I don't think we can do much here, but let me know otherwise. This will though force clients to handle with nullability explicitly. For example:

```
val viewState = useLiveData(liveData) ?: error("should not be null")
```
- **useFlow not using tree props**: astreet I did not find any usage of `TreeProps` in the `useFlow` - but maybe I'm looking to the wrong places. So at this moment, there is no unified solution (and I'm not even sure we need one).

- **Custom lifecycle owner**: astreet nicholeic I believe this might have a use case, but I wanted to explore later on. One possible way out, would be to give the ability to pass a specific `LifecycleOwner` and if so, it would override the default one.

issue.body:
Put together a skeleton of Aggregation Fuzzer. Similar to Expression Fuzzer, but
intended to test aggregate functions and aggregation operator itself.

This initial version generates single global aggregation using one aggregate
function and runs it on a single randomly generated vector. It already found 2
crashes in approx_percentile and approx_most_frequent: #3099 and #3101.

- run aggregations on multiple batches of data;
- run both global and partial aggregations using multiple grouping keys;
- run aggregations using multiple aggregate functions;
- support aggregate functions with generic signatures.

The structure of the Aggregation Fuzzer is similar to Expression Fuzzer.

- AggregationFuzzerTest is the entry point with the main() method.
- AggregationFuzzerTest hard-codes the skip-list and calls

Use cpp.template to handle nested value correctly

Summary:
User can use `cpp.type` to replace thrift field with C++ native type.

When replacing container with nested type, we will generate incorrect type tag, e.g.

```
struct Foo {
  1: map<i32, set<string>> (cpp.type = "std::unordered_map<int32_t, std::unordered_set<std::string>>") field
}
```

This generates the following type tag

```
type::cpp_type<
  std::unordered_map<int32_t, std::unordered_set<std::string>>,
  type::map<type::i32_t, type::set<type::string>>>
```

When we loop over the `Foo::field`, value type `std::unordered_set<std::string>` won't match type tag `type::set<type::string>>`, which confused op library.

This diff replaced the code with

```
typedef set<string> (cpp.template = "std::unordered_set") UnorderedSetString
struct Foo {
  1: map<i32, UnorderedSetString> (cpp.template = "std::unordered_map") field
}
```

So that it generates the correct type tag

```
type::cpp_type<
  std::unordered_map<int32_t, std::unordered_set<std::string>>,
  type::map<type::i32_t, type::cpp_type<std::unordered_set<std::string>,
                                        type::set<type::string>>>>
```

commits.message:
Add thread memory tracker util class to compute object size

Summary:
Add a util class `ThreadMemoryTracker` to help compute object size when enabling size-awareness.
The basic idea is
- Use Jemalloc util function(`thread.allocatedp` and `thread.deallocatedp`) to calculate allocated memory and deallocated memory in the current thread:
```
  memory usage = allocate memory - deallocated memory
```
- Get the currently used memory before and after the object construction, the difference is the object memory:
```
   get before memory usage
   ...construct object
   get after memory usage
   object size = after memory usage - before memory usage

```

Example:
```
// initialize memory tracker only at the beginning
ThreadMemoryTracke tMemTracker;
...

auto beforeMemUsage = tMemTracker.getMemUsageBytes();
...construct the object
auto afterMemUsage = tMemTracker.getMemUsageBytes();
auto objectSize = LIKELY(afterMemUsage > beforeMemUsage)
                        ? (afterMemUsage - beforeMemUsage)
                        : 0;
```

issue.body:
Introduces an alternative F14 style interleave layour for HashTable. This layout alternates tags and pointers to payload. Each group takes two cache lines: 16 bytes of tags, 8 * 48 bytes of pointers in the first cache line and 8*48 bits of pointers in the second cache line. A hash table that is expected to hit frequently, i.e. a group by table, will benefit from this layout since the tags and pointers most often share one cache miss and always share the TLB lookup.

Adds optional counters for hash lookups and collisions.

simplifies the hashProbe concept by passing the table as an argument as opposed to different fields of the table.

Uses SIMD for an array hash table probe. Previously this was limited to group by tables.

commits.message:
Add support for LiveData observability

Summary:
# Context

In this diff we are adding the initial support for live data observability.

## API

At this moment we have two API proposals:

```
fun <T> ComponentScope.useLiveData(liveData: LiveData<T>): T?

fun <T> ComponentScope.useLiveData(
    liveData: LiveData<T>,
    vararg keys: Any?,
    initialValue: () -> T?
): T?
```

Some examples of how it could look like to be used:

```
val viewState = useLiveData(viewStateLiveData) ?: error("should not be null")

val viewState = useLiveData(viewStateLiveData) { ViewState("hello", ..) } ?: error("should not be null")
```

## Behavior

- The `LiveData` is only be observed when the `Lifecycle` is in an `Active` state `(>= STARTED)`.
- The `LiveData` stops propagating updates when the `Lifecycle` is in an inactive state (`PAUSED/STOPPED`).
- The `LiveData` can resume updates observation when navigating between `PAUSED/STOPPED` to `STARTED/RESUMED` states.
- The `LiveData` stops being observed (and removes the observer) when the `Lifecycle` moves to `Destroyed`
- The `LiveData` stops being observed (and removed the observer) if the `ComponentTree/LithoView` is released (since the `useEffect` is cleaned up).

## Hooking the `LifecycleOwner`.

When observing a `LiveData` we need a reference to the appropriate `LifecycleOwner` (which is usually an `Activity` or `Fragment`).  The way I'm proposing to plug this is that we would store the `LifecycleOwner` as a `TreeProp` when create the `LithoView` with the `AOSPLithoLifecycleProvider`. This would allow the clients to specifiy for their case which is the most appropriate `LifecycleOwner`.

This goes along also with the side initiative we have to make people use more the `AOSPLithoLifecycleProvider` so that they have more reliable visibility callbacks.

**Things to note/Open Questions**
- **Usage of `keys`**:  At this moment I don't see the point of `keys`; in theory it would be a way to invalidate the observation, but it would simply trigger a new observation afterwards. I just added it here because the `useFlow` also has it, but Im failing to see a good use case for it. If we don't see any advantage for now, I would propose to remove it.

- **Null returns**: The `LiveData` API always return nullable types. For that reason our API is forced to also return nulls. I don't think we can do much here, but let me know otherwise. This will though force clients to handle with nullability explicitly. For example:

```
val viewState = useLiveData(liveData) ?: error("should not be null")
```
- **useFlow not using tree props**: astreet I did not find any usage of `TreeProps` in the `useFlow` - but maybe I'm looking to the wrong places. So at this moment, there is no unified solution (and I'm not even sure we need one).

- **Custom lifecycle owner**: astreet nicholeic I believe this might have a use case, but I wanted to explore later on. One possible way out, would be to give the ability to pass a specific `LifecycleOwner` and if so, it would override the default one.

- run aggregations using multiple aggregate functions;

Use cpp.template to handle nested value correctly

Summary:
User can use `cpp.type` to replace thrift field with C++ native type.

When replacing container with nested type, we will generate incorrect type tag, e.g.

```
struct Foo {
  1: map<i32, set<string>> (cpp.type = "std::unordered_map<int32_t, std::unordered_set<std::string>>") field
}
```

This generates the following type tag

```
type::cpp_type<
  std::unordered_map<int32_t, std::unordered_set<std::string>>,
  type::map<type::i32_t, type::set<type::string>>>
```

When we loop over the `Foo::field`, value type `std::unordered_set<std::string>` won't match type tag `type::set<type::string>>`, which confused op library.

This diff replaced the code with

```
typedef set<string> (cpp.template = "std::unordered_set") UnorderedSetString
struct Foo {
  1: map<i32, UnorderedSetString> (cpp.template = "std::unordered_map") field
}
```

```
type::cpp_type<
  std::unordered_map<int32_t, std::unordered_set<std::string>>,
  type::map<type::i32_t, type::cpp_type<std::unordered_set<std::string>,
                                        type::set<type::string>>>>
```

commits.message:
Add thread memory tracker util class to compute object size

Summary:
Add a util class `ThreadMemoryTracker` to help compute object size when enabling size-awareness.
The basic idea is
- Use Jemalloc util function(`thread.allocatedp` and `thread.deallocatedp`) to calculate allocated memory and deallocated memory in the current thread:
```
  memory usage = allocate memory - deallocated memory
```
- Get the currently used memory before and after the object construction, the difference is the object memory:
```
   get before memory usage
   ...construct object
   get after memory usage
   object size = after memory usage - before memory usage

```

Example:
```
// initialize memory tracker only at the beginning
ThreadMemoryTracke tMemTracker;
...

auto beforeMemUsage = tMemTracker.getMemUsageBytes();
...construct the object
auto afterMemUsage = tMemTracker.getMemUsageBytes();
auto objectSize = LIKELY(afterMemUsage > beforeMemUsage)
                        ? (afterMemUsage - beforeMemUsage)
                        : 0;
```
